  "prompt": "What determines the specific heat of a substance?",
  "response": "The specific heat capacity of a substance is determined by several factors, including its molecular structure, bonding, type of atoms or molecules, degrees of freedom, and its physical state (solid, liquid, or gas). Here\u2019s how these factors influence the specific heat:\n\n1. **Molecular Structure**: Different substances have different molecular arrangements, which affect how they store energy. Complex molecules with more atoms or larger structures tend to have higher specific heat because they have more internal degrees of freedom.\n\n2. **Bonding and Interactions**: The types of chemical bonds (ionic, covalent, hydrogen, etc.) and intermolecular forces present in a substance influence its ability to absorb and store heat. For example, substances with strong bonds or extensive hydrogen bonding might have different heat capacities than those with weaker interactions.\n\n3. **Degrees of Freedom**: The degrees of freedom refer to the different ways in which a molecule can store energy. This includes translational, rotational, and vibrational motions. Polyatomic gases, which have more degrees of freedom compared to monoatomic gases, typically have higher specific heat capacities.\n\n4. **Atomic and Molecular Mass**: Lighter molecules usually have higher specific heats because they can move more rapidly and have more modes of vibration, which tends to increase the capacity to store thermal energy.\n\n5. **Phase of the Substance**: Specific heat can vary depending on whether the substance is in a solid, liquid, or gas phase, as the physical state affects molecular movement and freedom. Typically, gases have higher specific heats at constant pressure than solids or liquids due to the work done in expanding the gas.\n\n6. **Temperature**: The specific heat of some substances can change with temperature. As temperature increases, more vibrational modes can be accessed in a molecule, effectively changing the specific heat.\n\nUnderstanding these factors helps in predicting and explaining the specific heat of various substances and how they interact with heat energy.",
